For decades of pre-1989 autocracy people were denied fair elections, and the government did not tolerate any dissent. When we were rebuilding our democracy in the 1990s, we did everything we could to make sure everybody would be able to vote, and do so freely, without any government interference. 

Also, gerrymandering is much harder to pull off in Poland, because our voting districts generally simply follow standard administrative divisions into communes (gminy), counties (powiaty) and regions (wojew√≥dztwa). Some manipulation is still possible, but to a very limited extent compared to the US. Also because we have a proportional electoral system in most polls - we elect as many as 20+ representatives from a single electoral district, so the winner does not usually take all, and thus gerrymandering makes less sense.

@John 

Look at it like this: people like finishing puzzles. When something prevents or hinders a solve, it's only natural they don't enjoy it, right? When this obstacle is something the solver was unfamiliar with, even though they are otherwise leading a full and reasonably successful life, they may begin to feel sore about it. After all, people usually consider themselves the main protagonists of the world they live in. 

It took me many months to accept I will sometimes simply be unable to solve a puzzle unaided, despite being a well read, well travelled man who spent 22 years getting his education. When I started doing these puzzles, for a long time I really did feel treated unfairly when I failed. Only then came the realization I fail because of who I am, not because of what the puzzles are like. It took a kind of stoic approach that does not come easy to most people I should think.

