In Poland "makaron" means "pasta". Macaroon cookies were unknown for decades, but when globalization brought them along, we needed a name for them. We settled on "makaroniki", which literally means "little pastas" and makes no sense at all. It always feels weird to me to see that name attached to a cookie.

We have always had a somewhat similar style of cookie - with dough spread between two layers of softish dough, but unlike macaroons, they did not involve any almonds. They are called "markizy", singular "markiza", which means the same as a marquess, as well as an awning. Language is weird.

